In programming, the keyword `static` is used in various contexts to modify variables, methods, or classes. Here are some common uses of the `static` keyword in programming:

1.  **Static Variables**: In a class, a static variable is shared by all instances of the class. It is created when the class is loaded and remains in memory until the class is unloaded.

    ```java
public class MyClass {
    public static int myVariable = 10;
}
```

    In this example, `myVariable` is a static variable. It is shared by all instances of `MyClass`.

2.  **Static Methods**: A static method belongs to the class itself, not to any instance of the class. It can be called without creating an instance of the class.

    ```java
public class MyClass {
    public static void myMethod() {
        System.out.println("Hello, World!");
    }
}
```

